                        <H3 style="font-style: underline">2. <u>Analyse your thoughts: 

                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Since dealing with the habit of overthinking is a mind game, you need to observe the nature of your thoughts to combat the habit of overthinking. This involves a few simple steps:

                            <br>
                            a. <b>Recognise your thought patterns: </b>Understand how and why one thought leads to another? Does one thought instigate similar thoughts or different ones? Take note of these details to become more aware of your cognitive process.

                            <br>
                            b. <b>Recognise anxiety-provoking stimuli: </b>Certain stimuli in our environment act as stressors and provoke anxiety-inducing thoughts. It is crucial to recognise such triggers and eliminate them as much as possible. For example, social media apps like Instagram and talking to certain people can promote overthinking. It is best to cut down your exposure to such stimuli.

                            <br>
                            c. <b>Assess the rationality of your thought:</b>Most of the thoughts that cross our minds are highly irrational and unlikely to come true. So, it is essential to assess the rationality or practicality of your thoughts. For example: If you feel anxious about an exam and think, "I will fail", then challenge this irrational thought. Reason with your mind and say, "It is less likely that I will fail. I might get a mediocre grade, but I will pass for sure". Here, the key is to substitute irrational thoughts with more rational ones. 

                        </p>
                       

