                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">7. <u>Allot a "Worry Time":



                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Some scholars have suggested an effective method of allotting a specific time to worry in your day (Howley and Miller). For instance, you assign yourself 10 to 15 minutes in a day to worry as much as you want. Whenever you find yourself worrying about a thought outside of this allotted time, tell yourself that you will think about it in the designated time. This will prevent you from overthinking throughout the day and reduce the time spent worrying. 
                        </p>

  <br>
                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">8. <u>Seek Professional Help:

                            
                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            It's great if these strategies work out for you. If they don't and you feel like your problems are getting out of your hand, seek a psychologist and undertake therapy (Howley and Mirror). A psychologist is professionally trained to guide individuals in solving their problems. Therefore, it is advisable to seek professional help and guidance when needed. 

                        </p>

